description.text: Cage for keeping a pet cricket.  Half of the parts are 3D printed.  The bars of the cage are made with 3 mm bamboo skewers.

You will need 3 mm bamboo skewers and some super glue. The cage is designed to be 60 mm tall, but you can adjust the measurements as desired.
  • Print your parts.
  • Cut your bamboo skewers.
    A. Cut four 61.5 mm pieces for the gate.
    B. Cut five 63 mm pieces for the supports.
    C. Cut twenty seven 64.5 mm pieces for the bars.
  • Glue the four 61.5 mm pieces into the gate.
  • Glue the five 63 mm pieces into the five recessed holes in the base. (see photo)
  • Insert the gate through the holes in the top.
  • Glue the top to the five supports on the base. (see photo)
  • Put a drop of glue in one of the recessed holes in the top, insert one of the 64.5 mm bars through the matching hole in the base, add another drop of glue to the hole in the base.
  • Repeat step 7 for each bar.
  • Insert one bracket into the top, glue if necessary.
  • Insert handle into first bracket and snap other handle bracket into the top.
  • Add cricket!

So you have ignored the better judgement of those around you and spawned an army of creepers http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8346. Now you are locked in your room using the light from your redstone powered computer to keep you safe. As you cry like the little girl you are because you ran out of torches while trying to recover from the creeper that exploded while you were playing god. Now they are spawning themselves and you can't do anything about it. If only there was a hero to save you, but wait your 3d Printer still is working for now. That is it you can spawn a hero to save you and risk his own plastic life to save you from the demon creepers that are outside your door. There may still be hope to save you...Nothing will get rid of the shame of your girlish scream though. Since having made the creeper and the interest in Minecraft items I have seen since posting it, I decided we needed a Minecraft guy. Well, to be honest I was working on the pig first but this had a higher demand and less original coding... This model is as basic as they come, no hat, glasses, no distinguishing marks of any kind. Due to the nature that is a Minecraft avatar I wanted something that could be customized. I did make a second arm model labeled the tool arm, this arm has a hole that passes through it that allows for the holding of tools and swords that are coming soon. As with my creeper model this is parametric an coded at roughly 1mm per pixel. The dimensions are below: Head: 8x8x8
Body: 8x4x12
Arm: 4x4x12
Leg: 4x4x12 I will not post the dimensions for the tools when I get them done because coding them makes my head hurt let alone figuring out dimensions. This is still a work in progress because I am still developing the weapons for the model. As with the creeper and the guy these will be almost completely faithfully duplicated in a pixel to mm manor. Except when I get a wild hair to think that I can make it look better in 3d. Disclaimer: The Minecraft Guy and anything else related to minecraft is owned by Markus Persson aka Notch and Mojang AB. I claim no rights to anything but the wild idea to make my own creeper. I loved the game and everything they are doing so you should support them if you aren't already. Note: I am putting this as a Attribution - Creative Commons license simply because I don't know what else to put it as. If anyone from Mojang has a problem with this model or the Licensing that I have set for it let me know and I will change it. Update 1: The .stls provided below are at 8x scale. This makes the creeper come out to about 8 inches. I will be uploading a standardized scale .stl at a later date. As I work on the rest of a set of minecraft models I learn how huge these things are. It looks as though the animals won't print on my makerbot hence the change in scaling, when I get one that works for everything. I was not in the right mind when I started this project but the creeper keeps telling me that I must finish or he will explode. Hopefully the minecraft guy will save me when he respawns. Update 2: I have cleaned up the the code in the .OpenSCAD file so that way it is easier to read and edit. I have also completed the code for the full set of tools. I have uploaded the guy and all of his tools in my new standardize 5x scale. This will make it so he is the same size as the sheep and any future models.

• Print 1 of each Head, Body and Leg set. Print 2 arms, these can be any combination of the two types regular and tool. Preferably in a white color, for easy of coloring the skin. If anyone knows a better way to do this please let me know.

  • Using markers or paint color your Guy's skin. This is meant to be a blank slate where you can create what ever you would like. If you just want to the basic Minecraft guy great if you want a custom skin go for it. It is up to you.

  • Attach legs to the body.
    At the 8x scale 3mm filament works perfect. cut off 8 small piece and use as connectors. Glue in place either by melting with acetone or using super glue.

  • Attach Arms to the body.
    At the moment due to lack of any good idea on how to attach the arms and make them pose-able they are attached by a single piece of filament in the same manor as the legs. This should allow for the arms to be posed at the time of creation.

  • Place head on body.
    The print layers on mine allow the head and body to stick together fairly well with mine while allowing the head to spin. It has been suggested to add support for magnets to hold everything together but I haven't tried as of yet.

  • Release upon the horde of Creepers that you created because you thought it was cool. Hopefully he can save you. If you find after the destruction of the creepers that you are missing random chunks of furniture and house and strange blocky structures are building built while you sleep. I then recommend that you encase you guy in a jail made of bedrock for safe keeping.

description.text:
FINAL UPDATE 6/1/13 REV3
I was having trouble with the prints lifting at the corners when they are so large. Since helper disks won't work with lithophanes without messing them up, I made an option to add them to the original STL file. It also puts them under the hangers. Look for it in the slicing and printing tab.
Fixed hanger depth to 1/2 of total print. UPDATE 5/30/13
I added the option of 1 or 2 lines of text in it's own pane along the bottom of the gallery. You can select the spacing, font, height, and shade of the finished letters. See new instructions for special character use with write.scad.
I also fixed some minor bugs with differences and the height of the finished photo portion. UPDATE 5/24/13
tbuser fixed the customizer backend, and now this thing is working! I changed the way the hangers are laid out, and made different tabs for images for the upper and lower rows. This is an update to the thing published by MichaelAtOz - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:78719
It allows you to input up to 8 images and arrange the layout of the panes in the gallery. You can choose the border width, hanger size, and the row and column layout for your pictures. The panes are about 50mm square, with two rows and four columns possible. With all eight panes, it should fit onto a standard Replicator bed.

UPDATE 5/30/13
Special characters in the write.scad portion of this thing can be used in the following way:
The double quote (") can be inserted by using one single quote (')
A single quote apostrophe (') can be inserted with the backtick (`) next to the number 1 on standard windows keyboard.
The backslash \ can be inserted using a pipe (|) Shift backslash on standard windows keyboard. I like to use MS Paint (I know, you thought it was not good for anything!). I resize a picture to about 200 pixels (be sure to check the Maintain Aspect Ratio box). Then, I crop it while looking at the bottom information bar until it is where I want and also a square. Then resize again to 100x100 and save with a different name. It helps to use pictures that are similar in tone, like school pictures, or pictures that all have about the same amount of light. In the example picture, the center photo was a light black and white photo, and the outer ones are school pics. Load pictures into slots 1-4 for the top row, and 5-8 for the bottom row. You can have from 1-8 lithophane panes in your gallery. Don't forget to check the invert box on each picture! Choose your border width, hanger size and number, and play around with your layout. Be sure to set your slicing settings and use them when you set up the print.

title: Java Gear Generator: Involute and Fillet

description.text: I have been working on making gears lately and found the process harder than it should have been. I found some parametric equations for a 1/2 tooth involute and fillet profile here (http://eng-tips.com/viewthread.cfm?qid=272852&page=5) and whipped up a Java program to generate points in either a tab delimited csv format or an ibl format for those of us using CAD software. Gears can be generated in metric or standard. EDIT: I updated the code to support profile shifting for gears with small numbers of teeth, as well as more descriptive prompts. Also uploaded sample output files for a 32 pitch, 20 degree, 32 tooth gear.

You will need the Java Developer's Kit to compile and run the code, freely available from Sun Microsystems 1.) Download the file Gears.java and compile it using %> javac Gears.java
2.) Run the file using %> java Gears
3.) Follow the on screen instructions
4.) Input the points into the design software of your choice NOTICE: All software is provided without warranty of any kind. Read the source code before using. Run at your own risk.

description.text:
Hello everyone! Im finaly uploading my quadcopter frame stl files after so many requests! Im uploading for free so you can share with me your experiences with your own builds, and some improvements you may have made to it! Here is the building process video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cMusBnFvW2A The model itself is not a finished product. I designed it to be printed as thin as possible ( only 2 shells), so it can stay together with the carbon fiber as an internal skeleton without adding too much weight, and to get rid of the demolding process. After 2 layers of carbon fiber this thing got realy strong !!! But of course you can try to make a 3d printed (only) version! i recomend 5 shells for that and no infill at all! Please notice that you are going to need i little extra time with a drilling machine like Dremel on this. And a powerfull fast glue too like zap a gap or locktide do put body parts and arms toghether. Small holes on the inside part of the arms are needed to pass the wires too. I allso glued the landing gear to the body.
I also drilled the upper cover out, and laminated it separatly, so a have acces to all the electronics. Onde this is not a finished project, dont forget your sense of adventure! Hope you enjoy the model! Dont be afraid to ask any questions!

Intro

The goal of this project was to create a small, modular, printable quadcopter body. I aimed to keep this as simple as possible.   
The quadcopter is made up of a core, and 4 arms. All arms are identical.
Parts List

• Turnigy 2900KV Brushless Outrunner OR Turnigy Park480 Brushless Outrunner 1320kv
  • Turnigy Plush 6A ESCs or HobbyKing 6A ESC 0.5A UBEC
  • 5030 Props
  • 5030R Props
  • 1000mAh 2S NanoTech LiPo (or similar)
  • KK2 Flight Controller
  • 8 x 12mm or 15mm M3 Bolts
  • 4 x 40mm M3 Bolts
  • 10 x M3 Nuts
    • Read assembly instructions for more details.
Change List

v2: Spacing change, removal of extra weight. Landing strut available if you don't want to use M3 screws
v1: Initial release

• Print 4 arms (2 shell, 30% infill recommended)
  • Print 1 core (1 shell 100% infill recommended)
  • Assemble arms to body (12mm or 15mm M3 screws + nuts)
  • Place 40mm M3 screws into end of arms. These will be your landing pins. Secure with M3 nuts.
  • Attach other hardware.

title: High resolution Weather Remote (actually a rock)

description.text:
This is a high resolution scan of a special rock that controls the weather. Use it as a casing for your DIY remote project for your kids. They will love it.  
The original was found in the forest on a windy day. I told my son I found a Remote !!! Many times with success I turned on and off the wind and sun. Luckily when he tried it with his sister (3 and 2 years) the sun and wind also did turn on and off.  
In cases it didn't work I told them not to point to the ground but upwards to the sky !!!  
Let's make this rock famous and use this high resolution STL for DIY remotes around the world. Comment with a picture of your RF or IrDA device.

The STL has been build up using roughly 14 scans, done with a structured light scanner and extra points for reference. For better result the rock was sprayed grey. In the picture you can still see some residue. Structured light scanner uses a 1000 lines.
Maximum resolution 0.06 mm depending on the size of the object. Meshlab was used to align the point clouds and export the STL.

The "front" is intentionally oversized to cover the edges and then some, the raised portion fits inside the cut frame.  I printed in transparent ABS to use as lenses.  Might put some red LEDs in the frame tube tied to the brake light to act as extra brake lights, could also make blinkers out of them, or running light or whatever.

I put a piece of paper over the cut frame and did a crayon rubbing.  Took measurements with a caliper.  Created in Google Sketchup Make, 2015, exported to stl, moved over to my DaVinci printer (jailbroken) and printed away.

title: Stepper motor gear for Reprap Mendel with flat on motor shaft

description.text: This is a gear I designed to make because I broke one of the wooden gears provided with the Techzone Laser-cut Wooden Mendel Kit.  I used this design to cut 1/16" plastic (laser-engraving laminated material).  Photos include one showing a couple of wafers along with the damaged wooden gear, and another photo showing the assembled stack on the motor shaft.

Prior to cutting with the laser, I put double-sided tape on the plastic so that all the pieces would stick together.  The central hole was tried several different sizes until I found a size that would push onto the shaft and still be tight.  Depending on the thickness or stretchiness of the material you work with, you may need to adjust the size of the central hole.  With the material I used, after a few layers were stacked on to the shaft, it was very rigid and would not move.

comments.text: I have had good results cutting similar layered gears in plywood then dipping them in fluid epoxy before assembling.
comments.author: Lanthan

comments.text: ha, layers of plastic, is that to make up for a very low power laser? The upside with it is that you could impovise herringbone gears with it, if you make the other gear in the same fashion. But why not printing it, you had a 3d printer at your disposal.. :)
comments.author: JelleBoomstra

comments.text: The laser I have use of is a 40W model.  The material I used is 1/16" laminated PVC-type material ("laserable" plastic - actually made for plastic engraved labels).  I attached thin double-sided tape to the plastic before cutting it, then as I assembled it, the wafers stuck together and became very rigid.  Each individual wafer was a very tight fit on its own.

title: MakerFarm i3v Z rod support Remix with Extruder Wire Holder and Tool Holder

description.text:
This adds a hook for keeping the extruder wire harness from hitting the threaded rod and some holes for small tools used on the printer. I have one slot in the back of this I was going to put some wire cutters in, but thought they might fall out at some point & cause a problem. I used Printbus's modification of Kkessler's original version as the starting point for this design. I added some holes for attaching a wire tie if you want. I also added some ears to the corners in the print that were lifting off the bed. You can turn them off by commenting out a couple of lines in the openscad file. I am also thinking of carrying this design further by adding some more depth to the back for hanging a plastic cover for covering my wires. If you print something really tall, you might have a problem with the wire hitting the extruder especially if you wire tie it in place. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:636381 & http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:410126 for further details on the original design. Updated 6/10/2015
I uploaded a repaired version of these stl files.

comments.text: I tried one of the with-bearing models (on bottom IIRC) and slic3r wasn't emitting the right bits.. something wrong; I ended up printing the no bearing model and it came out very nicely .. it was huge, but exactly fit the 10" prusa i3v; the hole for the rod is a little large so I'm not sure the piece is doing much, but it fits exactly right (nice job!)
comments.author: skeezix

comments.text: I usually run these openscad generated files thru the netfabb basic program to repair any problems before uploading. I obviously missed this. Thanks for spotting it. I replaced the stl files with repaired copies if you want try printing this again with the bearing hole. For your reference you might want to get a free copy of the netfabb basic program from: http://www.netfabb.com/downloadcenter.php?basic=1 I usually use this software on files generated from openscad & also a lot of files I download from thingiverse. Glad the part fit for you. I did go through a few prints to get the sizing to fit the wood correctly, although I only printed the part that fit on the wood before printing the whole part.
